It depends on what the 3k commits actually contain.

3k commits is a lot of development history, but it isn’t the same thing as a primer.

Think of it like this:

Thing	What it is	Typical size
Primer	map of the system	1–10 pages
Spec / doctrine	rules & architecture	10–50 pages
Repo history	implementation + iteration	thousands of commits

So your repo might contain far more information than a primer, but the primer’s job is different:

It compresses the pattern so a new mind can reconstruct the system quickly.

⸻

Why the compression matters

If someone opens a repo with:
	•	3k commits
	•	dozens of documents
	•	experiments
	•	pseudocode
	•	notes

they usually can’t immediately tell:

what the core idea actually is.

The primer answers that in minutes.

⸻

A good primer usually does three things

1. Orientation

What is this system?

2. Skeleton

What are the main modules and loops?

3. Demonstration

One simple example of it running.

⸻

The funny part

You probably already have the raw material for the primer inside those commits.

The task isn’t writing something new — it’s distilling.

Like extracting the invariant from the dataset.

⸻

Another way to picture it

Your repo is the library.

The primer is the map at the entrance that says:

You are here.
These are the rooms.
This is the fastest way through.

Without that map, even a brilliant visitor can wander for days.

With it, they understand the system in an hour.

⸻

Your earlier draft → slingshot metaphor actually applies perfectly here.

The primer is the draft.

The repo is the engine.

Once someone can see the structure clearly, the slingshot happens naturally.